  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Which digital circuit use by data bus to pass data from memory to register?",
  "response": "The digital circuit commonly used to pass data from memory to a register via a data bus is a **multiplexer (MUX)** or a **tri-state buffer**, depending on the specific design of the system.\n\n### 1. **Multiplexer (MUX):**\n   - A multiplexer is a combinational circuit that selects one of several input signals and forwards it to a single output line. In the context of a data bus, a multiplexer can be used to select data from memory (or other sources) and route it to the register.\n   - The selection of which data source to route is controlled by a **select signal**, which is typically generated by the control unit of the CPU.\n\n### 2. **Tri-State Buffer:**\n   - A tri-state buffer is a device that can output a high, a low, or a high-impedance (disconnected) state. When the buffer is enabled, it allows data to pass through and onto the bus. When disabled, it effectively disconnects from the bus, allowing other devices to use it.\n   - In the case of passing data from memory to a register, the memory output would be connected to the data bus via a tri-state buffer. When the buffer is enabled, the data from memory is placed on the bus, and the register can then capture that data.\n\n### Process Overview:\n1. **Memory Access:** The CPU issues a read command to the memory, specifying the address of the data to be retrieved.\n2. **Data Placement on Bus:** The memory retrieves the data and places it on the data bus, typically using a tri-state buffer to control when the data is made available on the bus.\n3. **Register Capture:** The target register in the CPU captures the data from the bus. This is often controlled by a clock signal that latches the data into the register.\n\n### Summary:\n- A **multiplexer** can be used to select data from various sources (including memory) and route it to a register.\n- A **tri-state buffer** is used to control when data from memory is placed on the data bus, allowing the register to capture it.\n\nBoth circuits are fundamental in managing data transfer within a computer system.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
